00023 /* MACROS that hide the C interface implementations from the
00024  * generated code, which makes it a little more understandable to the human eye.
00025  * I am very much against using C pre-processor macros for function calls and bits
00026  * of code as you cannot see what is happening when single stepping in debuggers
00027  * and so on. The exception (in my book at least) is for generated code, where you are
00028  * not maintaining it, but may wish to read and understand it. If you single step it, you know that input()
00029  * hides some indirect calls, but is always referring to the input stream. This is
00030  * probably more readable than ctx->input->istream->input(snarfle0->blarg) and allows me to rejig
00031  * the runtime interfaces without changing the generated code too often, without
00032  * confusing the reader of the generated output, who may not wish to know the gory
00033  * details of the interface inheritance.
00034  */
00035

00123 /* The 4 tokens defined below may well clash with your own #defines or token types. If so
00124  * then for the present you must use different names for your defines as these are hard coded
00125  * in the code generator. It would be better not to use such names internally, and maybe
00126  * we can change this in a forthcoming release. I deliberately do not #undef these
00127  * here as this will at least give you a redefined error somewhere if they clash.

00226 ANTLR3_API pwswdParser
00227 wswdParserNewSSD   (pANTLR3_COMMON_TOKEN_STREAM instream, pANTLR3_RECOGNIZER_SHARED_STATE state)
00228 {
00229     pwswdParser ctx;        /* Context structure we will build and return   */
00230     
00231     ctx = (pwswdParser) ANTLR3_CALLOC(1, sizeof(wswdParser));
00232     
00233     if  (ctx == NULL)
00234     {
00235                 // Failed to allocate memory for parser context
00236                 //
00237         return  NULL;
00238     }
00239     
00240     /* -------------------------------------------------------------------
00241      * Memory for basic structure is allocated, now to fill in
00242      * the base ANTLR3 structures. We initialize the function pointers
00243      * for the standard ANTLR3 parser function set, but upon return
00244      * from here, the programmer may set the pointers to provide custom
00245      * implementations of each function. 
00246      *
00247      * We don't use the macros defined in wswdParser.h here, in order that you can get a sense
00248      * of what goes where.
00249      */
00250 
00251     /* Create a base parser/recognizer, using the supplied token stream
00252      */
00253     ctx->pParser            = antlr3ParserNewStream(ANTLR3_SIZE_HINT, instream->tstream, state);
00254     /* Install the implementation of our wswdParser interface
00255      */
00256     ctx->cmd_line       = cmd_line;
00257     ctx->pipecreator    = pipecreator;
00258     ctx->process        = process;
00259     ctx->pipeto = pipeto;
00260     ctx->binary = binary;
00261     ctx->param  = param;
00262     ctx->file   = file;
00263     ctx->redir  = redir;
00264     ctx->exe    = exe;
00265     ctx->inredir        = inredir;
00266     ctx->outredir       = outredir;
00267     ctx->free                   = wswdParserFree;
00268     ctx->getGrammarFileName     = getGrammarFileName;
00269     
00270     /* Install the scope pushing methods.
00271      */
00272 
00273         
00274     
00275 
00276         
00277     /* Install the token table
00278      */
00279     PSRSTATE->tokenNames   = wswdParserTokenNames;
00280     
00281     
00282     /* Return the newly built parser to the caller
00283      */
00284     return  ctx;
00285 }
